column361:
Consent Statement

Please review the following information about this study.


	
	TASK: If you agree to participate in this study, we will ask you to answer a series of questions about a series of images. 
	
	
	BENEFITS:  There will be no direct benefits to you other than compensation.
	
	
	RISKS: We don't anticipate any risks from participating in this study to be greater than normal activity.
	
	
	PRIVACY:  No personally identifying information will be revealed to anyone other than the researchers conducting this study. The records of this study will be kept private. We do not collect any personally-identifying information.  
	
	
	SECURITY: All records pertaining to this research are stored on encrypted servers. Only the researchers will have access to the records.
	
	
	CHOICE:  Participating in this study is completely voluntary. If you decline to participate, it will not affect your current or future relationship with the researchers.
	
	
	WITHDRAWAL: If you agree to participate, you are free to withdraw at any time. You can withdraw by closing the browser window. If you withdraw, your responses will not be recorded. 
	
	
	QUESTIONS: You may ask any questions about the research at any time. If you have questions about the research after you complete the task, please contact Arvind Satyanarayan.
	
	
	QUESTIONS: If you are not satisfied with response of research team, have more questions, or want to talk with someone about your rights as a research participant, you should contact the MIT Committee on the Use of Humans as Experimental Subjects (COUHES).
column362:
Eligibility

You are eligible for this study if and only if:


 You are over 18 years of age.
 You are sighted and do not have color blindness or other color vision impairment.
 You are comfortable reading and writing in English.
 You have JavaScript enabled in your browser.

column28: I can't say without knowing what it's about
column54: From the style I think it comes from the Economist, which I tend to trust as being relatively unbiased as a news outlet. I tend to trust their representation of the data, and that they would collect data from relatively unbiased sources (e.g. UN, World Bank, etc).  I'm not sure if I'm supposed to be answering about the person working for The Economist, or organization itself.
column88: i understandy why someone might use the greenery rather than straight bars, and I think i agree with that choice depending on the their purpose, especially if it is to persuade or get attention.
column122: I think it's effective in getting my attention, and maybe that's what the purpose is! The specific quantitative size of differences between groups may be exaggerated or inaccurate by the use of 3D but I suspect based on the design aesthetic the purpose is to get my attention and maybe have me reshare the post
column133: a right wing activist or organization
column156: The american flag as background really makes me think this is about a polarized (and likely right wing) topic, and so the person or organization is likely not like me and not with values that agree with.  It just seems unecessary that you would put the US flag in the background except to act as a dogwhistle
column164: i'm curious about the use of three consecutive pie charts
column167: really hard to tell seems like it could be advertising or a company or agency, like in an annual report
column190: really hard to say much about this figure. it seems kind of generic. probably not from an academic paper, but likely in an annual report or advertisement or something like that. just not really sure.
column198: it looks like there is a strong trend in the timeseries, and so I'm curious about what the information is about.
column218: probably tableau and then cleaned up in design software
